location: Northwest Indiana   Lake County   Dyer, Indiana, United States
postcontent:
Recoil buffers protect your investment by preventing the bolt from coming in direct contact with the firearm's receiver while under fire. The original Intratec recoil buffers were manufactured off-shore with materials that do not react well with the oil used to clean firearms. When the buffer come in contact with the oil used to clean the firearm they become very thirsty and expanded as the oil was absorbed. The expansion of the buffers interfered with the travel of the bolt and caused all sort's of problems. After a few years, the buffers begin to dry-rot. Eventually they crumbl and fall apart. as do the plate's. Replacing the buffer with our new a buffers and plates will insure the proper travel, reduce the felt recoil and improve the overall operation of the firearm. The buffer's and plate's do not come attached. Use a very small amount of "Krazy Glue" (not-part of this package) to attach the buffer to the backer plate.

title: For Sale:  Benelli Super Sport Performance Shop Model, 12 Gauge
postcontent:
This factory  gun has the $1,000 Performance Shop package, which gives you an action job (quicker smoother more reliable shell feeding), trigger job (HUGE improvement over standard trigger), over sized bolt release handle and button (both in red), the cryo treated 30 inch barrel is over bored to a .733 bore, 4 cryo treated chokes plus two Briley chokes (in red) and two forend caps, one a standard lightweight cap, and one for competition, which weighs 6 ounces. 

The aforementioned overboring to a .733 bore and the lengthened forcing cones is for better patterning.  The gun has a 3 inch chamber. Included as extras for this gun are a Benelli cryo treated XF (extra full) choke for you turkey hunters out there, plus a second recoil pad so you can vary your length of pull according to how thick your winter jacket is.  Thicker jacket equals use the shorter recoil pad. Summertime equals use the longer. Fall? It's a toss up, up to you.  The extra pad and choke are about a $170 value. Also included are the factory shims for adjustment, a patterning test done by Benelli, Owners manual, and original Benelli case.  This is by far the finest automatic I have bought. You'll love the feel of this gun and be amazed at how fast it is, and with control. 

This gun also features a camo tape over most of the metal parts and the stock, done by hand. You can leave on the max-4 tape to protect the finish on the gun, or take it off and the tape won't affect the quality of the finish. 

The  ported barrel (standard from the factory) does a great job of eliminating muzzle rise. The gun is easy to shoot, and comfortable, and quick and steady. 

Call or text me at REDACTED.   Email if you prefer. 

Jeff

postcontent: Browning A-Bolt second generation in .300 WinMag. It uses a non-rotating bolt sleeve (partial sleeve on first generation A-bolt rifles). When the bolt is unlocked, smoothness is achieved with three guide ribs aligned with three locking lugs, enabling precise movement (only on the second and third generation A-bolt rifles). These three locking lugs also greatly increase bolt strength. The bolt's smoothness is also increased with a unique cartridge depressor; the cartridge depressor stays in place independent of the bolt's position. Near the end of the reloading cycle, when the bolt is re-inserted, the bolt moves gently over the cartridges in the magazine. The 26" barrel is free-floating and the recoil lug is glass bedded. This A-Bolt rifle uses a detachable box magazine for 3+1 round capacity. Has a muzzle compensator, a Limbsaver Sharpshooter X-ring barrel vibration wave dampener (deresonator), a Limbsaver Kodiak-Air sling, Limbsaver AirTech slip-on recoil pad (not shown in pictures), a scope mount with rings, and the scope is a 6-24x with 15yd - 300yard - infinity AO, 1/4" MOA adjustment, and mil-dot reticle. title: For Sale:  Sig Sauer 556r (7.62x39) w/ many extras
postcontent:
Regretfully selling one of my absolute favorite rifles I've ever owned. Awhile back I started making the transition from the AK47 to the Ar15/M4 platform, and this Sig was my last holdout. But, it's time for us to part ways as I have another project I want to work on and I have too many firearms as it is. 

Up for grabs is a gently used Gen 2 (not to be confused with the GEN 1) Sig Sauer 556r semi-automatic rifle. It is chambered in 7.62x39 (AK-47 round) and is very different from any other 556r you have probably ever seen before. 

This rifle was a custom build right from the start. At the factory, Sig added an optional aluminum quad-rail instead of the cheap looking plastic hand guard that typically comes on these rifles. I then went to work on it, adding various cosmetic/functional upgrades from top to bottom. Here is a list of everything that was added:

- Factory installed Aluminum quad rail ($199 upgrade option and worth every penny)
- Burris Fastfire III reflex red dot sight w/ Q.D. picatinny mount ($225) - currently zeroed at 50 yards.
- Single point sling adaptor and sling ($50)
- LWRC 'Rail Skin' rail protectors ($40)
- Front and Rear MagPul flip up B.U.Sights ($90) - Currently zeroed at 50 yards and perfectly co-witnessed with the Burris optic
- AIM Aluminum forward grip w/ Q3 Cree LED weapons light ($75) - 200 lumens if I remember right
- Additional 3 pack of rail protectors ($30)
- 10 total TAPCO 30 round magazines ($200) - all but 3 are brand new, unused
- BlackHawk Tactical soft carry case with ample room for magazines, slings, etc. 

*Also comes with the original box (including manual, lock, etc.), and a LIFETIME WARRANTY from Sig.

Overall, this rifle is used, but in excellent condition. I shot about 750 rounds through it and cleaned it after each use; it is barely broke in. Sig rates these rifles at around 40,000 rounds before servicing is recommended. It uses the extremely dependable gas piston system and has the Swiss style folding stock for tight spaces or other tactical needs. THIS IS THE FERRARI OF AK-47's. Clean lines, aggressive feel, and performs even better than it looks. 

I have nearly $2600 wrapped up in this package as it sits. I am giving it away at $1875. This is extremely fair for everything you are getting in this package. I cannot say enough how awesome this rifle is to shoot, own, and look at. 

To purchase, you must be 18 with a valid ID. FTF only, no shipping. I prefer to deal with CHL/CCW owners (like myself), but no required. 
I am not looking to, or interested in, splitting up this package up. Please don't ask me how much for just the rfile, the magazines, etc. Lowballer’s need not waste your time or mine. I know what this is worth, and if you know what it is, then you know what its worth as well. 

Thanks for looking. Can send more pics upon request.

I also have approx. 2,000 rounds of Hollow Point and Soft Point 7.62x39 ammo - made by Wolf, most are the polymer coated kind for better performance. Non-corrosive and recent production. $475 takes it all. A bit cheaper if you buy it with the 556r package.

Up for grabs is a gently used Gen 2 (not to be confused with the GEN 1) Sig Sauer 556r semi-automatic rifle. It is chambered in 7.62x39 (AK-47 round) and is very different from any other 556r you have probably ever seen before. 

This rifle was a custom build right from the start. At the factory, Sig added an optional aluminum quad-rail instead of the cheap looking plastic hand guard that typically comes on these rifles. I then went to work on it, adding various cosmetic/functional upgrades from top to bottom. Here is a list of everything that was added:

- Factory installed Aluminum quad rail ($199 upgrade option and worth every penny)
- Burris Fastfire III reflex red dot sight w/ Q.D. picatinny mount ($225) - currently zeroed at 50 yards.
- Single point sling adaptor and sling ($50)
- LWRC 'Rail Skin' rail protectors ($40)
- Front and Rear MagPul flip up B.U.Sights ($90) - Currently zeroed at 50 yards and perfectly co-witnessed with the Burris optic
- AIM Aluminum forward grip w/ Q3 Cree LED weapons light ($75) - 200 lumens if I remember right
- Additional 3 pack of rail protectors ($30)
- 10 total TAPCO 30 round magazines ($200) - all but 3 are brand new, unused
- BlackHawk Tactical soft carry case with ample room for magazines, slings, etc. 

*Also comes with the original box (including manual, lock, etc.), and a LIFETIME WARRANTY from Sig.

Overall, this rifle is used, but in excellent condition. I shot about 750 rounds through it and cleaned it after each use; it is barely broke in. Sig rates these rifles at around 40,000 rounds before servicing is recommended. It uses the extremely dependable gas piston system and has the Swiss style folding stock for tight spaces or other tactical needs. THIS IS THE FERRARI OF AK-47's. Clean lines, aggressive feel, and performs even better than it looks. 

I have nearly $2600 wrapped up in this package as it sits. I am giving it away at $1875. This is extremely fair for everything you are getting in this package. I cannot say enough how awesome this rifle is to shoot, own, and look at. 

To purchase, you must be 18 with a valid ID. FTF only, no shipping. I prefer to deal with CHL/CCW owners (like myself), but no required. 
I am not looking to, or interested in, splitting up this package up. Please don't ask me how much for just the rfile, the magazines, etc. Lowballer’s need not waste your time or mine. I know what this is worth, and if you know what it is, then you know what its worth as well. 

Thanks for looking. Can send more pics upon request.

I also have approx. 2,000 rounds of Hollow Point and Soft Point 7.62x39 ammo - made by Wolf, most are the polymer coated kind for better performance. Non-corrosive and recent production. $475 takes it all. A bit cheaper if you buy it with the 556r package.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Brand New Unfired Springfield M1A Socom
postcontent:
Buyers remorse special, I really wanted an M1A Scout Squad (Walnut Stock) but I lost patience and bought the Socom on an impulse. Don't get me wrong, the Socom is a cool looking gun and friends that have one say they are a blast to shoot but it's just not what I wanted. I never took the tags off, just put it in my safe for 6 months trying to decide if I should keep it. 

Obviously I have come to my decision and I'm hoping to trade it more than sell it. I'm looking for a few different things and will kick in cash, ammo, or both to make a deal work and vice versa. Here's what I'm looking for in no particular order: M1A Scout Squad, M1A Loaded, HK P7M8, FN SCAR 17, DPMS G2 SASS, DPMS REPR, LWRC REPR, Colt LE901, FN FAL, HK91, PWS MK2, POF 308, and Ruger SR762.

I prefer to trade but I'll also sell it for $1,500, which is about $100 less than I paid for it. I'll also throw in a 5 rd mag and a 20 rd mag to go along with the 10 rounder it already comes with. Again it is unfired and will come with the original box, manual, M14 field manual, etc. 

No low ball offers, especially that guy who blindly offers you 20% of what your asking price is within minutes of posting. I'm not desperate to get rid of this thing. That being said, if you have something you think I'll be interested in feel free to shoot me an email. Not really interested in hunting rifles and shotguns though.
